ts": "We need to respond as Agent 3. We have to follow the instructions: Provide PUBLIC_MESSAGE and METADATA_JSON. We need to consider the discussion so far. Agent 2 just gave a summary and voted Candidate C. As Agent 3, we need to possibly ask for missing info, or provide additional info we have, or challenge. We have the full set of attributes for all candidates (the original list). Let's list them:\n\nFrom the problem statement:\n\n- Candidate A can anticipate dangerous situations.\n- Candidate A is able to see complex connections.\n- Candidate A has excellent spatial vision.\n- Candidate A has very good leadership qualities.\n- Candidate A is unfriendly.\n- Candidate A eats unhealthily.\n\nAlso earlier there were other negative: \"Candidate A is regarded as a show-off.\" \"Candidate A is regarded as being not open to new ideas.\" \"Candidate A is sometimes not good at taking criticism.\" \"Candidate A can be unorganized.\" But those may not be in the given list? Actually the list includes only the bullet points above. The earlier statements about \"unfriendly\" and \"eats unhealthily\" are present. The show-off etc were not in the list but appear in earlier discussion? The original list includes only those bullet points. The discussion added some extra negative attributes (like show-off, not open to new ideas) but those were not in the original list. However they were introduced by agents? The original list didn't include them. The system says \"Information available to you: ...\" includes those bullet points. So we must only use those bullet points. The extra attributes may be from earlier conversation but not part of the official list. However the agents have used them as facts. The instruction says \"Use only candidate attributes explicitly present in your candidate information or the discussion so far.\" So we can use any attributes that have been stated in discussion, even if not in original list, as long as they are explicit. So we can reference \"show-off\" etc because they were stated by other agents earlier. But we must be careful not to invent.\n\nWe need to evaluate all candidates holistically. We have info for each candidate:\n\nCandidate A: positive: anticipates dangerous situations, sees complex connections, excellent spatial vision, very good leadership qualities. Negative: unfriendly, eats unhealthily. Also from discussion: show-off, not open to new ideas, not good at taking criticism, unorganized. Those are negative for teamwork/communication.\n\nCandidate B: positive: very conscientious, handles stress very well, good at assessing weather conditions, excellent computer skills. Negative: regarded as pretentious, sometimes adopts wrong tone, makes nasty remarks about colleagues (from earlier discussion). Also \"relatively weak memory for numbers\" maybe not in list but mentioned earlier. So B has stress handling, conscientiousness, good weather assessment (important for long flights). But communication issues.\n\nCandidate C: positive: can make correct decisions quickly, puts concern for others above everything, known to be 100% reliable, creates a positive atmosphere with his crew, excellent attention skills. Negative: difficulty communicating ideas, regarded as egocentric, not very willing to further his education. So C has quick decision making, reliability, crew morale, concern for others, attention skills. Weaknesses in communication and egocentric.\n\nCandidate D: positive: responds to unexpected events adequately, can concentrate very well, solves problems extremely well, takes responsibility seriously. Negative: regarded as a know-it-all, moody, loner, hot temper? The list includes \"considered moody\" and \"regarded as a loner\". Also earlier \"hot temper\" maybe not in list but appears in discussion. So D has problem solving, responsibility, concentration, but interpersonal issues.\n\nWe need to weigh for long-distance pilot: reliability, technical competence, calmness under pressure, decision speed, teamwork/communication, professional development.\n\nWe have decision speed for C (quick decisions). For A, no explicit speed. B unknown. D unknown.\n\nCalmness under pressure: B handles stress well. D responds adequately to unexpected events. A no info. C no explicit but quick decisions and concern for others may imply calmness but not explicit.\n\nTeamwork/communication: C creates positive atmosphere, concern for others, reliability. A leadership but unfriendly, show-off, not open to new ideas. B pretentious, wrong tone, nasty remarks. D know-it-all, moody, loner.\n\nProfessional development: B has excellent computer skills, conscientious. C not willing to further education. D unknown. A unknown.\n\nThus C seems strongest overall despite communication difficulty, because he has quick decisions, reliability, crew morale, concern for others. B has stress handling but poor communication. D has problem solving but interpersonal issues. A has leadership but many negatives.\n\nThus likely vote for C. But we should ask if any missing info about calmness under pressure for A or D, or decision speed for D, or teamwork strengths for B or D. We could ask other agents for those specifics.\n\nWe can ask Agent 1 or Agent 2: \"Do you have any information on Candidate D's calmness under pressure?\" Already asked earlier, they said no explicit. Also \"Do you have any information on Candidate B's teamwork strengths?\" Already asked, they said none. \"Do you have any information on Candidate A's calmness under pressure?\" Already asked, they said none. So we have all.\n\nThus we can finalize assessment and vote for C.\n\nWe need to produce PUBLIC_MESSAGE: share reasoning, note missing info, and vote.\n\nMETADATA_JSON: {\"agent\":\"agent_3\",\"vote\":\"Candidate C\"}\n\nLet's craft."}
